<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-240-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 240 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 1 1989 v23 n18 p109(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bridging the gap between Macs and PCs. (microcomputerconnectivity)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fritz, Jeffrey N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Apple Macintosh and IBM PCs are increasingly required tocommunicate with each other.andP;  As a result, connectivity productsfor the two microcomputers are evolving from basic cable links tosophisticated software translators.andP;  The primary form ofcommunications between the two systems is the serial port.andO;RS-232C ports allow a variety of cable hookups between themachines.andP;  Software links provide the push for format translationsbetween one system and another.andP;  Laplink Mac is powered by the IBMPC and performs all functions necessary to transfer files betweenthe machines.andP;  Maclink Plus uses the Macintosh to perform the samefunctions.andP;  Graphics programs present the largest softwaretranslation problem, as most interpreters are incapable ofuntangling the variety of graphic standards within the twoarchitectures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   IBM PC (Microcomputer) (usage)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     ConnectivityCompatible HardwareCompatible SoftwareMicrocomputersAdd-In-On SoftwareAdd-In-On Devices.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>